India Equity Movers: Anil Ambani Companies, eClerx, Sun TV

-- B y   A m e y a   K a r v e
-- 
2011-06-03T12:16:50Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-03/india-equity-movers-reliance-ada-companies-sun-tv-spicejet.html
The following companies had unusual
price changes in  India  trading. Stock symbols are in parentheses
and share prices are as of the 3:30 p.m. close in Mumbai.  The Bombay Stock Exchange Sensitive Index, or Sensex, fell
117.7, or 0.6 percent, to 18,376.48, the steepest decline in
more than a week. The gauge rose 0.6 percent in the week, its
first advance in three weeks. The BSE 200 Index decreased 0.7
percent to 2,282.42.  Reliance ADA Group: Shares of  Reliance Communications Ltd. (RCOM) 
 rose 3.8 percent to 93.35 rupees and  Reliance Capital
Ltd. (RCAPT)   added 2.6 percent to 524.1 rupees.  India’s Judge O.P. Saini rejected pleas in  New Delhi  by
public interest litigators seeking to probe Reliance ADA Group
Chairman  Anil Ambani  and others related to the 2008 sale of
mobile phone licenses.  eClerx Services Ltd. (ECLX)   surged 6.8 percent to a
record 830 rupees. About 1.2 million shares, or 4.2 percent
equity of the back-office service company, changed hands in
three blocks at 778 rupees each, according to data compiled by
Bloomberg. The buyers and sellers weren’t immediately known.  Hindustan Dorr-Oliver Ltd. (HDOR)   advanced 2.8 percent
to 66.5 rupees after it said it won a $85 million order from
Zambia’s Konkola Copper Mining Plc.  Reliance Power Ltd. (RPWR)   advanced 1.8 percent to 118.8
rupees, the biggest gain in a week. The Indian utility
controlled by Ambani was upgraded to “buy” from “accumulate”
by Amit Golchha, an analyst at Emkay Global Financial Services
Ltd. The brokerage set a price estimate of 153 rupees a share.  Sun TV Network Ltd. (SUNTV)   and  SpiceJet Ltd. (SJET)  
rebounded from a plunge yesterday on report India’s federal
investigator is probing an investment by  Malaysia ’s Maxis Group
into a business run by the Marans, whose family controls the
broadcaster and the discount carrier. Sun TV climbed 4.1 percent
to 283.75 rupees, the steepest advance in more than three
months, and SpiceJet increased 2.2 percent to 35.25 rupees, the
steepest since May 6.  The fall in share prices were due to “baseless
allegations,” Sun TV said in an exchange filing.  To contact the reporters on this story:
Ameya Karve in Mumbai 
 kgokhale@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
